Uncovering the joint distribution

Uncovering the joint distribution allows one to:

  • Understand the relationship between outcomes \(A\) and \(B\)
  • Use information about \(B\) to predict \(A\) (or vica versa)

Commonly used joint distribution for continuous data

Multivariate Normal Distribution

Multivariate Normal Distribution

MVN Parameters

\[\boldsymbol{\mu} = \left[\begin{array}{c}\mu_1 \\ \mu_2 \\ \vdots \\ \mu_p \end{array}\right]\ \ \ \Sigma = \left[\begin{array}{cccc} \sigma_{1,1} & \sigma_{1,2} & \cdots & \sigma_{1,p} \\ \sigma_{2,1} & \sigma_{2,2} & \cdots & \sigma_{2,p} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ \sigma_{p,1} & \sigma_{p,2} & \cdots & \sigma_{p,p} \\ \end{array}\right]\]

MVN Parameters

\[\mu_k = \text{Mean of outcome } k\]

\[\sigma_{i,k} = \text{Covariance of outcome } i \text{ and } k\]

\[\sigma_{i,i} = \sigma^2_i = \text{Variance of outcome } i\]

MVN Parameters

  • \(\boldsymbol{\mu}\) can be any value.
  • \(\Sigma\) must be a positive (semi-) definite matrix. (It must be a valid variance-covariance matrix.)

Note that \(\sigma_{i,j} = \sigma_{j,i}\), so \(\Sigma^t = \Sigma\).

MVN density function

\[ f_{\boldsymbol{X}}(\boldsymbol{x}) = (2\pi)^{-\frac{k}{2}}|\Sigma|^{-\frac{1}{2}}\exp\left\{-\frac{1}{2}(\boldsymbol{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu})^t\Sigma(\boldsymbol{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu})\right\}\]

\[ |\Sigma| = \det(\Sigma) = \text{determinant}(\Sigma) \]

Bivariate normal density function

If \(p = 2\), then

\[\boldsymbol{\mu} = \left[\begin{array}{c}\mu_1 \\ \mu_2\end{array}\right]\ \ \ \Sigma = \left[\begin{array}{cccc} \sigma_{1,1} & \sigma_{1,2} \\ \sigma_{2,1} & \sigma_{2,2}\\ \end{array}\right]\ \ \ |\Sigma| = \sigma^2_{1}\sigma^2_{2} - \sigma_{1,2}^2 = \frac{1-\rho^2}{\sigma^2_{1}\sigma^2_{2}} \]

Bivariate normal density function

If \(p = 2\), then

\[ (\boldsymbol{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu})^t\Sigma(\boldsymbol{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu}) = \\ \sigma_1^2(x_1-\mu_1)^2 + 2\,\sigma_{1,2}(x_1-\mu_1)(x_2 - \mu_2) + \sigma^2_2(x_2 - \mu_2)^2 \]

Bivariate normal density function

(continued)

\[ (\boldsymbol{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu})^t\Sigma(\boldsymbol{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu}) = \\ \sigma_1^2(x_1-\mu_1)^2 + 2\,\rho\sigma_1\sigma_2(x_1-\mu_1)(x_2 - \mu_2) + \sigma^2_2(x_2 - \mu_2)^2 \]

Bivariate normal density function

(continued)

\[ (\boldsymbol{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu})^t\Sigma(\boldsymbol{x} - \boldsymbol{\mu}) = \\ \frac{1}{(1-\rho^2)}\left[\frac{(x_1-\mu_1)^2}{\sigma^2_1} + 2\,\rho\frac{(x_1-\mu_1)}{\sigma_1}\frac{(x_2 - \mu_2)}{\sigma_2} + \frac{(x_2 - \mu_2)^2}{\sigma^2_2}\right] \]

Bivariate normal density function

Note that the bivariate normal can be re-parameterized from

\[\mu_1, \mu_2, \sigma_1, \sigma_2, \sigma_{1,2}\\ \text{to}\\ \mu_1, \mu_2, \sigma_1, \sigma_2, \rho\]

MVN with MLE and Method of Moments

One can estimate \(\hat{F}_{\boldsymbol{X}}(\boldsymbol(x))\) with maximum likelihood or method of moments.

\[ \hat{\boldsymbol{\mu}} = \left[\begin{array}{c} \text{sample mean of variable 1} \\ \text{sample mean of variable 2} \\ \vdots \\ \text{sample mean of variable } p \end{array}\right] \\ \hat{\boldsymbol{\Sigma}} = \text{sample variance-covariance} \]

MVN with MLE and Method of Moments

Hmisc::getHdata(nhgh)
d1 <- nhgh %>% 
  filter(sex == "male") %>%
  filter(age > 18) %>% 
  select(arml, leg) %>% 
  filter(complete.cases(arml, leg))
d1 %>% 
  ggplot() + 
  aes(x = arml, y = leg) +
  geom_point(col = "#00000050") +
  theme_minimal()

MVN with MLE and Method of Moments

MVN with MLE and Method of Moments

mu_hat <- colMeans(d1)
sigma_hat <- var(d1)

limits <- d1 %>% sapply(range)
x <- seq(limits[1,1], limits[2,1],length = 50)
y <- seq(limits[2,1], limits[2,2],length = 50)
xy <- expand.grid(x = x, y = x, KEEP.OUT.ATTRS = FALSE)
density <- dmvnorm(xy, mean = mu_hat, sigma = sigma_hat)
z <- array(density, c(length(x), length(y)))

MVN with MLE and Method of Moments

plot(d1, col = "#00000020", pch = 16)
contour(
    x = x
  , y = x
  , z = z
  , add = TRUE
  , col = "navy"
  , lwd = 2
  , drawlabels = FALSE
)
